{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n3183 (change 580, commit da27c5f30) delivered the merge-gate + snapshot ledger with a\ndivergent schema and verdict set vs. the APPROVED epic design (AC8/AC9 — the two ACs the\nepic completion-verifier correctly FAILED on). This story reworks commit 7 to the approved\ndesign AND performs the consumer cutover deferred from TS1 (in-toto payload) and TS2\n(commit-ancestry era) — the write-seam signing, the merge-gate, and the ledger all live in\nTHIS commit. Depends on TS1 and TS2. (User rejected the delivered design; see d7c0.)\n\n## Stack scoping (why the cutover is here + why TS2+TS3 land together)\nThis story AMENDS Gerrit change 580 = commit da27c5f30 (3183): `_seam.py`'s write-time\nsigning, `verify_authorship.py` (merge-gate), `compact.py`'s ledger, and `_state.py`'s\nauthorship summary. At this commit those consumers currently still call the epoch API that\nTS2 REMOVED (`epoch_for_position`, `verify_authorship_at_epoch`), so the commit-7 patchset\nis RED until this story rewires them — TS2+TS3 land together. `ensure_identity_for` (aliased\nby `create_placeholder`) lives in commit 6, so `create_placeholder` lands here too.\n\n## What\n\n### 1. Write-seam in-toto cutover (`_seam.py::_apply_authorship`)\nStamp `author_sig` by calling `authorship.sign_event_authorship(event, signing_key,\nprincipal=author_id)` (the in-toto Statement envelope) instead of\n`sign_authorship(canonical_bytes, ...)`.\n\n### 2. Merge-gate rewire (`verify_authorship.py`)\n- Refactor `_ScopedEvent`: REPLACE the `epoch: int | None` field with `commit_sha: str |\n  None` and `position: str | None` (the `{timestamp}-{uuid}` string). Live events populate\n  `position` from the filename and resolve `commit_sha` lazily; ledger entries populate both\n  from the ledger record (below).\n- LIVE-event content binding: parse the DSSE payload as an in-toto Statement and check\n  `subject[0].name == ev['uuid']` AND `subject[0].digest.sha256 ==\n  authorship.authorship_content_hash(ev)` (replacing the raw-bytes `envelope.payload !=\n  ev.payload` compare). Resolve the event's commit via\n  `authorship.resolve_event_commit(position, ticket_dir, repo_root)`.\n- Verify via `authorship.verify_authorship_at_commit(envelope, author_id, commit_sha,\n  position, repo_root=...)` (replacing `epoch_for_position` + `verify_authorship_at_epoch`).\n- **Four-way classification (the AC9 distinction):**\n  - `unsigned` — no `author_sig`.\n  - `unknown-author` — no `author_id` / not an identity ticket.\n  - `verified` — content binds AND `verify_authorship_at_commit` verified (key valid at the\n    event's commit).\n  - `key_not_valid_at_era` — content binds AND the signature is cryptographically valid\n    against SOME key in the identity's keyring (any era) BUT not one valid at the event's\n    commit. Decided by a NEW helper `authorship.verify_authorship_any_key(envelope,\n    identity_id, *, repo_root) -> registry.Verdict` that builds the trust root from ALL\n    keyring public keys (regardless of validity window) and runs ONE `registry.verify`\n    (boolean). valid-any-key AND NOT valid-at-commit ⇒ `key_not_valid_at_era`.\n  - `bad-signature` — content mismatch, malformed envelope, or verifies against NO key the\n    identity ever held (forged).\n- Add the verdict constant `KEY_NOT_VALID_AT_ERA = \"key_not_valid_at_era\"` and extend the\n  CLI `counts` dict (currently hardcoded `{VERIFIED, UNSIGNED, UNKNOWN_AUTHOR,\n  BAD_SIGNATURE}`) with the new key so it is tallied and printed. Document the display\n  grouping in the module docstring: `verified` / `unverified` (= `bad-signature` |\n  `key_not_valid_at_era` | `unknown-author`) / `unsigned`. When `resolve_event_commit` fails\n  for a LIVE event (unresolvable commit), the fail-closed verify yields non-`verified` and\n  the event is reported like any other non-verified event.\n\n## Migration note (unlanded + atomic)\nThe `authorship_ledger` wire format changes from `{event_uuid, author_id, author_sig,\nepoch}` to `{event_uuid, content_hash, signature, signer_pubkey, position}`. The stack is\nUNLANDED and lands atomically, so no real store holds an old-format ledger; there is no\nin-place snapshot migration to write (a pre-feature snapshot with no ledger is unaffected;\nthe reducer cache version bump from TS2 already invalidates stale reductions).\n\n### 3. Ledger (`compact.py::_build_authorship_ledger`)\nRecord `{event_uuid, content_hash, signature, signer_pubkey, position}` per signed folded\nevent, where:\n- `content_hash` = `authorship.authorship_content_hash(ev)` (TS1 digest).\n- `signature` = the event's `author_sig` (the DSSE Statement envelope).\n- `signer_pubkey` = the actual public key that verified the signature. Because SSHSIG verify\n  (`ssh-keygen -Y verify`) returns only pass/fail (NOT which key matched), determine it via a\n  new `authorship.identify_signer(envelope, identity_id, *, repo_root) -> str | None` that\n  iterates the identity's FULL keyring — ALL public keys, including REVOKED ones (so a valid\n  signature by a since-revoked key is still identified, enabling the later\n  `key_not_valid_at_era` classification) — verifying the envelope against each single-key\n  trust root and returning the first that passes. **Single None-policy:** if `identify_signer`\n  returns `None` (the signature verifies against NO key the identity ever held — a forged /\n  foreign signature), STILL record a ledger entry (never omit — omitting would hide a forged\n  event from the post-compaction merge-gate) with `signer_pubkey: null`; ledger verification\n  (Section 4) classifies a null-`signer_pubkey` entry as `bad-signature`. The record always\n  has exactly the five keys; `signer_pubkey` is a string or `null`.\n- `position` = `{\"commit_sha\": <resolve_event_commit(...)>, \"position\": \"<{ts}-{uuid}>\"}` —\n  the `position` string is the SAME `{timestamp}-{uuid}` value `verify_authorship_at_commit`\n  already consumes for intra-commit ordering (NO separate integer index; the string ordering\n  is the intra-commit index). `commit_sha` is resolved at compaction time.\n\n### 4. Ledger verification (`verify_authorship.py::_ledger_events` + `_verify_signed`)\nRewrite `_ledger_events` to read the NEW fields (`content_hash`, `signature`,\n`signer_pubkey`, `position.commit_sha`, `position.position`) — not the old\n`author_id`/`author_sig`/`epoch`. For a ledger entry, verification is self-contained:\ncrypto-verify the `signature` envelope against a ONE-key trust root built from\n`signer_pubkey`, check the Statement binds `content_hash`, and decide era from\n`position.commit_sha` against the SURVIVING snapshot keyring (retired KEY files folded into\nthe same snapshot; `resolve_event_commit` still finds a retired file's ADD commit via `git\nlog --diff-filter=A` across history) via `verify_authorship_at_commit`'s ancestry logic —\nemitting the same four-way verdict. A ledger entry with `signer_pubkey: null` is classified\n`bad-signature` directly (no key ever verified it). No raw event file needed.\n\n### 5. Verdict vocabulary (NOT the verify-signature schema)\n`verify_signature_result.schema.json` is the schema for the SEPARATE `rebar verify-signature`\ncommand (HMAC attestations: `unsigned|foreign_key|certified|mismatch`) — it is NOT touched.\nThe `verify-authorship` verdicts are its own vocabulary (string constants in\n`verify_authorship.py`): `verified`, `unsigned`, `unknown-author`, `bad-signature`, and the\nNEW `key_not_valid_at_era`, with the display grouping documented in that module. (The epic\nAC's phrase \"existing verify_signature_result verdicts\" is read as the verdict-vocabulary\nstyle, not a literal edit to that unrelated command's schema — reconciled per plan-review.)\n\n### 6. `create_placeholder`\nAdd `create_placeholder(provider, external_id, display_name, *, repo_root=None)` to\n`identity.py` as a thin idempotent alias over the delivered `ensure_identity_for`, and\nre-export it through the library facade chain so `rebar.create_placeholder(...)` is\nimportable: add it to `_lib_writes.py` and to `rebar/__init__.py`'s `__all__`/exports\nalongside `ensure_identity_for`.\n\n## Scope\nIn: the write-seam in-toto cutover, the merge-gate rewire to commit-ancestry + in-toto\ncontent-binding + the four-way `key_not_valid_at_era` verdict, the approved ledger schema +\nself-contained ledger verification, the `signer_pubkey`/`identify_signer` +\n`verify_authorship_any_key` helpers, and the `create_placeholder` alias + re-export. Out:\nauthorship payload machinery (TS1, done); era model machinery (TS2, done); docs/ADR (TS4).\nNOTE: `verify_signature_result.schema.json` is deliberately NOT modified.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A live signed event round-trips: with `identity.signing_key` set and a current\n  identity holding a valid key, an event written through the seam is classified `verified`\n  by `rebar verify-authorship` (proves the in-toto `_seam` stamping + the merge-gate in-toto\n  content-binding + commit-ancestry verify are wired end-to-end).\n- [ ] The SNAPSHOT authorship ledger records `{event_uuid, content_hash, signature,\n  signer_pubkey, position}` (position = `{commit_sha, position:\"<{ts}-{uuid}>\"}`) per signed\n  folded event; a round-trip test signs events, compacts (horizon=0, threshold=1), and\n  asserts `verify-authorship --all` returns `verified` from the ledger ALONE (raw event\n  files retired). A test also asserts the ledger record has exactly those five keys and that\n  `signer_pubkey` equals the actual signing key.\n- [ ] `verify-authorship` emits a distinct `key_not_valid_at_era` for an event whose\n  signature is cryptographically valid by a key the identity holds but which was NOT valid at\n  the event's commit (e.g. an event signed by a since-revoked key), distinct from\n  `bad-signature` and `unknown-author` (test drives the CLI and asserts the verdict string).\n- [ ] `bad-signature` is still emitted for a forged signature (verifies against no key the\n  identity ever held) and for a content-binding mismatch (test).\n- [ ] The `verify-authorship` verdict vocabulary exposes `key_not_valid_at_era` (a test\n  asserts the constant / that the CLI can print it) and the module documents the\n  `verified/unverified/unsigned` display grouping; `verify_signature_result.schema.json` is\n  unchanged (a test asserts its enum is still `unsigned|foreign_key|certified|mismatch`).\n- [ ] `rebar.create_placeholder(provider, external_id, display_name)` mints a keyless\n  placeholder identity, is idempotent on repeat (returns the same identity), and is\n  importable from the top-level `rebar` package (test).\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py` (in-toto cutover: stamp author_sig via sign_event_authorship)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/verify_authorship.py` (_ScopedEvent epoch->commit_sha/position; in-toto content-binding; verify_authorship_at_commit; key_not_valid_at_era four-way verdict; read new ledger)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/compact.py` (approved ledger schema + signer_pubkey via per-key identify)\n- `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` (verify_authorship_any_key + identify_signer helpers)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/identity.py` (create_placeholder alias over ensure_identity_for)\n- `src/rebar/_lib_writes.py` (re-export create_placeholder)\n- `src/rebar/__init__.py` (export create_placeholder for rebar.create_placeholder)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783888701011321001,"uuid":"298586e2-020c-462d-8c68-6f45cf5bec6a"}